Conclusion¶

The tools that made this presentation possible:

  • Jupyter notebooks for interactively developing Python
  • OSMnx is pronounced as the initialism: oh-ess-em-en-ex. It is built on top of NetworkX and GeoPandas, and interacts with OpenStreetMap APIs
  • contextily library to retrieve tile maps from the internet
  • nbconvert library to convert Notebooks to other formats
  • reveal.js & theme solarized to create slides with one palette
  • Netlify to deploy the presentation.slides.html to a custom URL
  • I wanted to create static maps that look like wall art.
  • After some experimentation I selected matplotlib as the base library
  • Rapid basic prototyping and plotting with matplotlib seemed straightforward. Customisation seems finicky with a steeper learning curve. https://stackoverflow.com/questions/40796117/how-do-i-make-the-width-of-the-title-box-span-the-entire-plot
  • Agentic AI was great at scaffolding the initial project and telling me "You're right". In this project I preferred googling blogs and reading docs to learn these new Python libraries

References¶

  • Boeing, G. (2025). Modeling and Analyzing Urban Networks and Amenities with OSMnx. Geographical Analysis, published online ahead of print. doi:10.1111/gean.70009

  • Interactive presentations from a Jupyter Notebook

  • x lines of Python: static basemaps with contextily
